ğŸ§ª Basic Examples:
ğŸ”¹ Example 1: Extract usernames from /etc/passwd (1st Column)
cut -d ':' -f 1 /etc/passwd

ğŸ”¹ Example 2: Get the shell of each user (7th Column)
cut -d ':' -f 7 /etc/passwd

âš™ï¸ Intermediate Usage:
ğŸ”¹ Example 3: Combine with grep to filter and extract
grep "bash" /etc/passwd | cut -d ':' -f 1

ğŸ”¹ Example 4: Extract multiple fields
cut -d ':' -f 1,7 /etc/passwd

ğŸ”¹ Example 5: Use with cat and pipe
cat users.csv | cut -d ',' -f 2


ğŸš€ Advanced Usage:
ğŸ”¹ Example 6: Extract AWS instance IDs from a CSV
cat ec2_instances.csv | cut -d ',' -f 1

ğŸ”¹ Example 7: Use with awk or grep for filtering and transforming data
grep "running" ec2_instances.csv | cut -d ',' -f 2
awk -F',' '/running/ { print $2 }' ec2_instances.csv

ğŸ’¼ Cloud Admin Use Cases for cut
ğŸ§° Use Case 1: Extract IAM usernames from CSV
cut -d ',' -f 1 iam_users.csv

ğŸ§° Use Case 2: Display instance IDs and names
cut -d ',' -f 1,2 ec2_instances.csv

ğŸ§° Use Case 3: Get list of public IPs from EC2 inventory
cut -d ',' -f 5 ec2_instances.csv


ğŸ§ª Combined Example: Real-Time Cloud Log Audit
ğŸ¯ Goal: Find all failed SSH login attempts and show IPs
grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log | cut -d ' ' -f 11
ğŸ“Œ Explanation:
grep searches for failed login attempts.
cut extracts the IP address from the log line.
.

ğŸ“ Summary Table
Command
Purpose
Cloud Admin Use Case
grep "ERROR" file
Find errors
Check logs
grep -r "pattern" dir/
Recursive search
Scan config dirs
cut -d ':' -f1
Extract usernames
Parse system user list
`grep "ssh"
cut -d ' ' -f11`
Extract IPs
grep -v "127.0.0.1"
Exclude local IPs
Filter access logs


ğŸ› ï¸ Practice Tasks
Find all successful SSH logins:

grep "Accepted password" /var/log/auth.log
Extract all public IPs from EC2 logs:

cat ec2_logs.txt | grep "PublicIp" | cut -d ':' -f 2
Show all users using /bin/bash:

grep "/bin/bash" /etc/passwd | cut -d ':' -f1
Extract CPU Usage and Strip the '%' Symbol
cut -d ',' -f3 perf_log.txt | cut -d ':' -f2 | sed 's/%//'



